Real world — when to use what:

+-------------------+-----------+----------------------------------+
| Subscriber        | Need SQS? | Why                              |
+-------------------+-----------+----------------------------------+
| Email             | ✗ No      | AWS manages email delivery       |
| SMS               | ✗ No      | AWS manages SMS delivery         |
| Lambda            | ✗ No      | Lambda scales auto               |
| HTTP endpoint     | ✓ Yes     | Endpoint can go down             |
| EC2 consumer      | ✓ Yes     | EC2 can go down                  |
| EKS pod           | ✓ Yes     | Pod can crash                    |
| Microservice      | ✓ Yes     | Service can be slow              |
+-------------------+-----------+----------------------------------+

SNS is push based — it broadcasts to all subscribers instantly but if a subscriber is down SNS retries limited times and then the message is lost forever.
SQS(Simple Queue Service) is added between SNS and the consumer to store messages safely — SQS retries unlimited times and even if all retries fail the message goes to DLQ and is never lost.

SNS can send directly to any subscriber like Email, SMS, Lambda without SQS.
SQS is only added when your own service like EC2 or EKS can go down — SQS stores messages safely until the service comes back up.

Key difference:

+------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+
|                        | SNS retry         | SQS retry         |
+------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+
| Retries                | Limited ✗         | Unlimited ✓       |
| Message after retries  | Lost forever ✗    | Goes to DLQ ✓     |
| Storage                | No ✗              | Yes ✓             |
+------------------------+-------------------+-------------------+
----------------------------------------
SNS vs SQS

SQS                          SNS
────────────────             ────────────────
Queue                        Topic
Pull (consumer pulls)        Push (SNS pushes)
One to One                   One to Many
Stores messages              No storage
Process later                Immediate
Decouple services            Notify many

When to use SQS:
  ✅ background jobs
  ✅ decouple services
  ✅ handle traffic spikes
  ✅ retry failed tasks

When to use SNS:
  ✅ notify multiple systems
  ✅ real time alerts
  ✅ fan out pattern
